# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thanos-metrics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:thanos-metrics/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] Grafana Tempo lets you scale tracing as far as possible with minimal operational cost and less complexity than ever before.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] The easiest way to get started is with Grafana Cloud, our fully composable observability stack.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] Grafana Tempo is an open source, easy-to-use, and high-scale distributed tracing backend.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] Tempo is cost-efficient, requiring only object storage to operate, and is deeply integrated with Grafana, Prometheus, and Loki.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] Tempo can ingest common open source tracing protocols, including Jaeger, Zipkin, and OpenTelemetry.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] The Tempo project was started at Grafana Labs and announced at Grafana ObservabilityCON in October 2020.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] It became generally available with the 1.0 release in June 2021.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] Tempo is released under the AGPLv3 license.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] Grafana Labs is proud to lead the development of the Tempo project, building first-class support for Tempo into Grafana, and ensuring Grafana Labs customers receive Tempo support and features they need.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] Grafana Labs is proud to lead the development of the Tempo project.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] High-volume, minimal-dependency tracing backend.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] Install, administer, and maintain your own instance.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] Offered as a fully managed service, Grafana Cloud Traces is an easy-to-use, massively scalable distributed tracing backend.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] Managed and administered by Grafana Labs with free and paid options for individuals, teams, and large enterprises.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] Get up to 50GB of traces at no cost in the free tier of Grafana Cloud.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] A scalable, secure, self-managed tracing service.
[src:thanos-metrics/oss-tempo] A self-managed option for organizations that have special requirements around data localization and privacy.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus originated at SoundCloud in 2012 and was accepted by the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) in 2016, graduating from incubation in 2018.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] It is commonly paired with Grafana for dashboard visualization and supports a wide range of exporters and integrations.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus was developed at SoundCloud starting in 2012, after the company found that its existing metrics tools, based on StatsD and Graphite, could not meet the demands of its containerized infrastructure.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] The design goals included a multi-dimensional data model, operational simplicity, scalable data collection, and a powerful query language in a single tool.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] The project was open source from the start and was adopted by Boxever and Docker users before any official announcement.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] The design was influenced by Borgmon, Google's internal time-series monitoring system, which treated time-series data as a source for alert generation.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] By 2013, Prometheus was in production use at SoundCloud.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] The project was publicly announced in January 2015.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] In May 2016, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation accepted Prometheus as its second incubated project, after Kubernetes.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] In August 2018, the CNCF announced that Prometheus had graduated from incubation.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus 1.0 was released in July 2016.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Subsequent releases through 2016 and 2017 led to Prometheus 2.0 in November 2017, which introduced a new storage engine with significantly improved performance and reduced disk usage.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] A typical Prometheus monitoring deployment consists of several components working together.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Exporters run on monitored hosts to collect and expose local metrics.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] The Prometheus server scrapes those exporters at a configured interval, aggregates the data, and stores it locally.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Alertmanager receives alerts from Prometheus and handles routing, grouping, and silencing before forwarding notifications.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Grafana is commonly used to build dashboards from Prometheus data.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Queries against all of these are written in PromQL, Prometheus's native query language.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus data is organized as named metrics, each optionally qualified by an arbitrary number of key-value label pairs.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Labels can identify the data source (server name, datacenter) or carry application-specific context such as HTTP status code, request method, or endpoint.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Querying in real time against any combination of labels is what makes the data model multi-dimensional.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus stores data locally on disk for fast writes and queries.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Metrics can also be forwarded to remote storage backends, including Grafana Mimir and other Prometheus-compatible systems.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus collects data through a pull model: the server periodically queries a configured list of targets (exporters) and aggregates the returned time-series values.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes several service discovery mechanisms to automatically locate targets in dynamic environments.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus provides its own query language, PromQL (Prometheus Query Language), which allows users to select and aggregate time-series data.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] The language includes time-oriented constructs such as the rate() function, instant vectors, and range vectors that return multiple samples per series over a specified time window.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Alert rules in Prometheus specify a condition and a duration; if the condition holds for that duration, Prometheus fires an alert to Alertmanager.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Alertmanager handles silencing, inhibition, and routing to notification destinations including email, Slack, and PagerDuty.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Additional targets such as Microsoft Teams can be reached through the Alertmanager webhook receiver interface.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes its own time series database.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Recent data (by default, one to three hours) is held in a combination of memory and mmap-backed files.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Older data is written to persistent blocks indexed with an inverted index, which suits Prometheus's label-based query patterns.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] A background compaction process merges smaller blocks into larger ones to reduce read overhead.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Durability against crashes is provided by a write-ahead log (WAL).
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes a basic expression browser but is not a full dashboard system.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Grafana is the standard pairing, querying Prometheus via PromQL to produce dashboards; the need to deploy and maintain Grafana separately is sometimes cited as an operational drawback.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus favors white-box monitoring, where applications publish internal metrics for collection.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Exporters and agents are available for many applications and systems.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] For transition from existing monitoring stacks, Prometheus supports several protocols: Graphite, StatsD, SNMP, JMX, and CollectD.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Metrics are typically retained for a few weeks.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] For longer retention, Prometheus can stream data to remote storage backends.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] An effort to standardize the Prometheus exposition format as OpenMetrics has gained adoption from several vendors, including InfluxData's TICK suite, InfluxDB, Google Cloud Platform, Datadog, and New Relic.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] The OpenMetrics specification is maintained separately from the Prometheus project.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] Prometheus client libraries are available for most major programming languages.
[src:thanos-metrics/prometheus-software] The POCO C++ Libraries expose Prometheus metrics through the `Poco::Prometheus` namespace.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] Grafana Tempo is an open-source, easy-to-use, and high-scale distributed tracing backend.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] Tempo lets you search for traces, generate metrics from spans, and link your tracing data with logs and metrics.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] Distributed tracing visualizes the lifecycle of a request as it passes through a set of applications.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] Tempo is cost-efficient and only requires an object storage to operate.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] Tempo is deeply integrated with Grafana, Mimir, Prometheus, and Loki.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] You can use Tempo with open source tracing protocols, including Jaeger, Zipkin, or OpenTelemetry.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] Learn about traces and how you can use them, how you can instrument your app for tracing, and how you can visualize tracing data in Grafana.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] Learn how tracing data can help you understand application insights and performance as well as help triage issues in your services and applications.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] Plan your deployment to meet your needs, deploy Tempo, test your installation, and instrument your app or services for traces.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] Learn about Tempo architecture, best practices, Parquet backend, dedicated attribute columns, and more.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] Learn about metrics created from traces, including the metrics-generator processor and TraceQL metrics.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] Inspired by PromQL and LogQL, TraceQL is a query language designed for selecting traces in Tempo.
[src:thanos-metrics/tempo-latest] This query language lets you precisely and easily select spans and jump directly to the spans fulfilling the specified conditions.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:thanos-metrics/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
